Original had a very saturated look (which is could be a

Many open-source projects have links to their github
repository directly on their home page. It makes it much
easier to find the repo and open-source is all about
accesibility. So I added it in.
Redesigned Natron's icon: I know that this could be pretty
contentious. But Natron's current icon says almost nothing
about Natron, other than it's name starts with N. My new
icon has a abstract representation of a node tree, which
would make more sense for a compositing software.
Out of respect for the original developers' work, I've created
two versions of each of the following pages.
The first version is my personal preference, which uses
well-established principles from user interface design. The
second uses most of the original, with minor tweaks.
For both versions, I thought that "Fully Cross Platform" was
a very inaccurate description for what the section talked
about, so I changed it. And I changed them to a color
scheme that matched my redesigned hero page.

Here, not much was changed (the original design was

Again, nothing much to change. I presonally perfer a card
layout, but the given layout is totally fine. The image didn't

I also added a timeline, but this was a personal choice as

Here, I mostly did a layout change, because I felt the

In addition, the first version has a custom donation page. I
get it that Natron has no active developers at the moment,
but donations could fund everyone from tutorial makers to
web designers/website maintainers or even Open Movies
(like blender). So I think that having a way to donate right
from the downloads page will be very useful for Natron.
